{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528501","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528501"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:43:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:43:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14307"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14307","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14307"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.48,0.14,0.1,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7002"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54442"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7002","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7002"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14307"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39951"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2117"},{"type":"tags","id":"2867"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16574"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30681"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39048"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39597"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40705"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45669"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54442"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of acute onset left lower quadrant abdominal pain. She denies fever, nausea, vomiting, or changes in bowel habits. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her abdomen is soft with localized tenderness in the left lower quadrant, but no guarding or rebound tenderness. Laboratory investigations reveal a white blood cell count of 8.5 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0). A CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis is performed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe radiologist reports a 2 cm lesion adjacent to the descending colon in the left lower quadrant. The lesion demonstrates a central dot of high attenuation surrounded by a ring of fat density. There is mild surrounding fat stranding, but no free fluid or pneumoperitoneum.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute diverticulitis","Epiploic appendagitis","Mesenteric panniculitis","Omental infarction","Acute appendicitis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and CT findings in this case are most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Eepiploic appendagitis\u003C/strong\u003E. This condition occurs when an epiploic appendage (small outpouchings of fat along the colon) becomes inflamed, often due to torsion or venous thrombosis. The key CT finding described is the \u0027target fat sign,\u0027 which is pathognomonic for epiploic appendagitis. This sign consists of a central dot of high attenuation (representing the thrombosed vessel) surrounded by a ring of fat density (the inflamed epiploic appendage) with surrounding inflammatory changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute diverticulitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with left lower quadrant pain, but would show diverticular inflammation, wall thickening of the colon, and often pericolic fat stranding on CT. The \u0027target fat sign\u0027 is not a feature of diverticulitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOmental infarction\u003C/strong\u003E usually occurs on the right side and presents as a larger area of inflamed fat without the characteristic \u0027target fat sign.\u0027 It typically causes more diffuse abdominal pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMesenteric panniculitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a chronic inflammatory condition of mesenteric fat. It typically presents with a more insidious onset of symptoms and shows a larger area of affected mesentery on CT, often with a \u0027misty mesentery\u0027 appearance rather than a focal lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute appendicitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with right lower quadrant pain and would show an inflamed, dilated appendix on CT. The location (left side) and the \u0027target fat sign\u0027 are not consistent with appendicitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEpiploic appendagitis is generally a self-limiting condition that can be managed conservatively with analgesia. The lack of systemic symptoms and normal white blood cell count in this case further support this diagnosis. Understanding the characteristic CT findings of epiploic appendagitis is crucial to avoid misdiagnosis and unnecessary interventions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Appendagitis epiploica is characterized by the \u0027target fat sign\u0027 on CT imaging, consisting of a central dot of high attenuation surrounded by a ring of fat density and inflammatory changes.","Appendagitis epiploica typically presents with acute, localized abdominal pain without systemic symptoms, often mimicking other acute abdominal conditions.","Conservative management with analgesia is usually sufficient for appendagitis epiploica, as it is generally self-limiting."],"references":["Giannis D, Matenoglou E, Sidiropoulou MS, et al. Epiploic appendagitis: pathogenesis, clinical findings and imaging clues of a misdiagnosed mimicker. Ann Transl Med. 2019 Dec;7(24):814. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6989878/","Ekladious A, Bhandari R. Epiploic appendagitis: a commonly undiagnosed non-surgical acute abdominal emergency. Intern Med J. 2023 Jul;53(7):1265-1268. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37474462/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39951"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14307"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39951","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39951"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-04T23:58:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-05T00:00:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7002"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54442"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.eme